public class NamedSet<T extends Named>
extends java.util.AbstractSet<T>
implements java.util.SortedSet<T>

A Set of Named WorkflowBean.

This set will guarantee to never contain more than one Named object per Named.getName().

It is also possible to retrieve values by name using getByName(String), or remove using removeByName(String). The names can also be found in getNames() and nameIterator()

Internally this set is backed by a TreeMap.

Author:
Stian Soiland-Reyes

add

public boolean add(T named)
Adds the Named WorkflowBean and returns true iff the set did not already contain an element with the same name. The element must not be null

If a different (object identity) element with the same name already exists in the set, the element will be replaced the new element and false will be returned.

Inserting the same object instance a second time will have no effect.

addWithUniqueName

public java.lang.String addWithUniqueName(T element)
Adds the Named WorkflowBean with a unique name if the name already exist.

Similar to add(Named), but if a (object identity) different element with the same name already exists in the set, the element to be inserted will be given a unique name before inserting.

This means that inserting the same object instance a second time will have no effect, as with add(Named).

The unique name is generated by appending _x to the existing name, where x is a number from 2 or higher. An existing numeric prefix will first be removed.

For example, if the set already contains elements named "fish", "fish_2" and "fish_5", but you try to insert a different element which is named "fish" or "fish_5", it will be renamed to "fish_3" before inserting.

Note: If the element is a Child instance, and it's Child.getParent() is not null (or this set) the renaming could potentially cause a conflict in the old parent set. (In the example above, if the element's old parent has a child "fish_3" it will be overwritten by this instance).

Parameters:
element - the Named WorkflowBean to add
Returns:
the final T#getName() after insertion
